00:26:05.523 --> 00:26:08.359
when I take the stand.

528
00:26:11.737 --> 00:26:13.823
Parasite.

529
00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.834
[Patty] Good morning.
Dr. Zax.

530
00:26:24.917 --> 00:26:27.044
- [Frank] Morning. ma'am.
- You go by Frank. right?

531
00:26:27.128 --> 00:26:30.172
Arthur was my father's name.

532
00:26:30.256 --> 00:26:32.675
Understood. And your brother
is George Zax?

533
00:26:34.385 --> 00:26:37.430
So you and your brother started
Zax Pharmaceuticals together.

534
00:26:37.513 --> 00:26:40.599
How would you describe
your roles in the company?

535
00:26:40.683 --> 00:26:43.144
I was the chief pharmaceutical
scientist

536
00:26:43.227 --> 00:26:45.521
and lead drug designer.

537
00:26:45.604 --> 00:26:48.232
And George was the president.

538
00:26:48.316 --> 00:26:51.152
CEO.

539
00:26:51.235 --> 00:26:52.504
What types of drugs
did you develop

540
00:26:52.528 --> 00:26:54.280
while you were at the company?

541
00:26:54.363 --> 00:26:56.657
Well. I began making. uh.
Zax Lax.

542
00:26:56.741 --> 00:26:58.451
[laughs] Laxatives.

543
00:26:58.534 --> 00:26:59.577
Okay.

544
00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:01.704
Antacids and then we moved

545
00:27:01.787 --> 00:27:04.498
onto opioids: Trimadone.

546
00:27:04.582 --> 00:27:05.916
Amurzyn...

547
00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.085
Objection!

548
00:27:08.169 --> 00:27:10.296
May we have a moment.
Your Honor?

549
00:27:10.379 --> 00:27:12.590
- [clearing his throat]
- What the fuck is that?

550
00:27:12.673 --> 00:27:14.425
- What is that?
- You'll find out.

551
00:27:14.508 --> 00:27:17.845
I'm filing a motion
in limine to exclude

552
00:27:17.928 --> 00:27:20.431
any information about Amurzyn
from his testimony.

553
00:27:20.514 --> 00:27:22.516
The f... No. you're not.
On what grounds?

554
00:27:22.600 --> 00:27:24.727
This case is about Trimadone.

555
00:27:24.810 --> 00:27:26.896
Any mention
of Amurzyn is irrelevant.

556
00:27:26.979 --> 00:27:28.981
Your Honor. Amurzyn is the crux
of our case.

557
00:27:29.065 --> 00:27:31.317
It proves they knew
that Trimadone was addictive.

558
00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:32.586
Any probative value
it may have...

559
00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:33.861
and I'm being generous here...

560
00:27:33.944 --> 00:27:35.529
is substantially outweighed

561
00:27:35.613 --> 00:27:37.239
by the unfair prejudice
and confusion

562
00:27:37.323 --> 00:27:39.617
of issues it brings with it.

563
00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:42.286
And if the jury's verdict is
tainted by any mention of it.

564
00:27:42.370 --> 00:27:45.081
that would be grounds
for an immediate appeal.

565
00:27:48.084 --> 00:27:51.796
I'm confident you'll find
some way around it.

566
00:27:51.879 --> 00:27:53.339
Ms. Solis-Papagian.

567
00:27:53.422 --> 00:27:55.132
You're a class act.
Your Honor. thank you.

568
00:27:55.216 --> 00:27:57.176
Motion is granted.

569
00:27:57.259 --> 00:27:59.428
Dr. Zax?

570
00:27:59.512 --> 00:28:04.225
You cannot mention Amurzyn at
any point during your testimony.

571
00:28:04.308 --> 00:28:06.435
Got it.

572
00:28:06.519 --> 00:28:08.270
[Patty exhales] Okay.

573
00:28:09.730 --> 00:28:11.732
[clears her throat]
So tell me...

574
00:28:11.816 --> 00:28:14.527
how does a company go
from making laxatives

575
00:28:14.610 --> 00:28:16.278
to opioids?

576
00:28:16.362 --> 00:28:18.072
Right there.

577
00:28:18.155 --> 00:28:19.674
- Right there? Huh.
- George. my brother.

578
00:28:19.698 --> 00:28:22.743
He wanted to move our company
into pain management.

579
00:28:22.827 --> 00:28:26.080
[Patty] Because pain management
is big business?

580
00:28:26.163 --> 00:28:29.542
Well. laxatives are only
really temporary relief.

581
00:28:29.625 --> 00:28:32.211
Pain management is...

582
00:28:32.294 --> 00:28:34.463
downtown. long-term.

583
00:28:34.547 --> 00:28:36.173
Hmm. so big money?

584
00:28:36.257 --> 00:28:37.967
Now you got it.

585
00:28:38.050 --> 00:28:40.052
Did you agree with his strategy?

586
00:28:40.136 --> 00:28:42.513
- I'm sorry?
- His strategy.

587
00:28:42.596 --> 00:28:44.932
- Did you agree with it?
- At the beginning. yeah.

588
00:28:45.015 --> 00:28:47.977
I wanted to come up
with a milder analgesic.

589
00:28:48.060 --> 00:28:50.646
Was there any reason
that you didn't want to make

590
00:28:50.729 --> 00:28:52.773
an opioid-based painkiller?

591
00:28:52.857 --> 00:28:54.024
Too addictive.

592
00:28:54.108 --> 00:28:56.193
- Oh.
- And we've had centuries

593
00:28:56.277 --> 00:28:58.237
to prove that: opium.

594
00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:00.364
morphine. codeine.

595
00:29:00.448 --> 00:29:03.701
So just to be clear.
opiates are used

596
00:29:03.784 --> 00:29:06.954
to manufacture
opioid-based painkillers?

597
00:29:07.037 --> 00:29:09.415
Yeah. they're man-made.

598
00:29:09.498 --> 00:29:12.251
So if everyone knows that
natural opiates are addictive.

599
00:29:12.334 --> 00:29:15.129
then why wouldn't it be
the same for synthetic opioids?

600
00:29:15.212 --> 00:29:17.756
Well. one reason is there was

601
00:29:17.840 --> 00:29:20.676
a piece in the New England
Journal of Medicine

602
00:29:20.759 --> 00:29:22.261
around 1980.

603
00:29:22.344 --> 00:29:25.764
where some doctors said
that opioids

604
00:29:25.848 --> 00:29:27.766
were not addictive...

605
00:29:27.850 --> 00:29:30.019
statistically speaking.

606
00:29:30.102 --> 00:29:32.438
Was the letter
peer-reviewed or...

607
00:29:32.521 --> 00:29:34.607
- scientifically backed up?
- No. ma'am.

608
00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:36.775
It was only a paragraph long.

609
00:29:36.859 --> 00:29:38.360
But George found it.

610
00:29:38.444 --> 00:29:41.405
He loved it because
he thought it gave us legal

611
00:29:41.489 --> 00:29:43.532
- cover.
- Were you swayed by the letter?

612
00:29:43.616 --> 00:29:45.034
I'm a scientist!

613
00:29:45.117 --> 00:29:47.286
Excuse me

614
00:29:47.369 --> 00:29:49.413
for raising my voice. but no.

615
00:29:49.497 --> 00:29:51.081
It was just an opinion piece.

616
00:29:51.165 --> 00:29:53.292
But George.
he didn't give a shit.

617
00:29:53.375 --> 00:29:55.711
Dr. Zax. language. please.

618
00:29:55.794 --> 00:29:58.589
So the test results
from Trimadone come back.

619
00:29:58.672 --> 00:30:00.674
What do they say?

620
00:30:00.758 --> 00:30:03.010
- It said it was addictive.
- So. Dr. Zax.

621
00:30:03.093 --> 00:30:05.054
why. if you knew

622
00:30:05.137 --> 00:30:07.973
that Trimadone was addictive.
why didn't you shelve it?

623
00:30:08.057 --> 00:30:09.934
Why didn't you work
on something else?

624
00:30:10.017 --> 00:30:13.020
I tried to.
I thought I had developed

625
00:30:13.103 --> 00:30:16.440
a non-addictive formula for it.

626
00:30:16.524 --> 00:30:18.484
But then suddenly I ran

627
00:30:18.567 --> 00:30:21.820
- into unexpected complications.
- Objection!

628
00:30:21.904 --> 00:30:25.658
- This guy.
- [Reiss] Dr. Zax. please refrain

629
00:30:25.741 --> 00:30:28.077
from mentioning Amurzyn.

630
00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:29.800
She asked me a question.
how am I supposed

631
00:30:29.870 --> 00:30:31.510
- to answer?
- [Reiss] Ms. Solis-Papagian.

632
00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:33.040
would you like
to try that again?

633
00:30:33.123 --> 00:30:35.125
Sure.

634
00:30:37.169 --> 00:30:39.880
If you knew
that Trimadone was addictive.

635
00:30:39.964 --> 00:30:41.507
why did you release it?

636
00:30:41.590 --> 00:30:43.467
Well. 'cause that was
George's call.

637
00:30:43.551 --> 00:30:45.678
He never seemed
really interested

638
00:30:45.761 --> 00:30:47.471
in any of my concerns.

639
00:30:47.555 --> 00:30:49.723
All he wanted to do was get

640
00:30:49.807 --> 00:30:52.142
Trimadone out there
as fast as he could.

641
00:30:52.226 --> 00:30:55.479
It was an undeniable
business model for him.

642
00:30:55.563 --> 00:30:59.316
An addictive. legal drug?

643
00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:01.443
Sells itself.

644
00:31:01.527 --> 00:31:03.779
What happened next?

645
00:31:03.862 --> 00:31:06.448
He pushed me out of the company.

646
00:31:06.532 --> 00:31:08.450
He got rid of me.

647
00:31:08.534 --> 00:31:11.287
Done. "You're done here."

648
00:31:11.370 --> 00:31:13.747
He wanted to be the only Zax

649
00:31:13.831 --> 00:31:16.250
in Zax Pharma.

650
00:31:16.333 --> 00:31:18.794
And went on to make billions...

651
00:31:18.877 --> 00:31:22.172
and I mean billions of dollars...

652
00:31:22.256 --> 00:31:26.135
off people's lives.

653
00:31:32.725 --> 00:31:34.768
Um. can I have a moment.
Your Honor?

654
00:31:34.852 --> 00:31:36.186
Just one moment.

655
00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:42.735
The jury loves him. I think
we should just end here.

656
00:31:42.818 --> 00:31:44.903
What are you... Are you...

657
00:31:44.987 --> 00:31:47.197
You want me to skip over
the mental health issues?

658
00:31:47.281 --> 00:31:49.241
Let Griffin address it. yeah.

659
00:31:49.325 --> 00:31:51.785
No way.
this is the perfect time.

660
00:31:51.869 --> 00:31:53.704
I insist.

661
00:31:53.787 --> 00:31:56.832
- They're gonna destroy...
- I insist.

662
00:31:56.915 --> 00:31:59.793
[Reiss] Um. Ms. Solis-Papagian.
anything else?

663
00:32:04.131 --> 00:32:06.508
Yeah. one more thing.
Your Honor.

664
00:32:06.592 --> 00:32:09.178
Frank. would you do me a favor?

665
00:32:09.261 --> 00:32:12.222
Would you take a look
at our fine jury. please?

666
00:32:13.932 --> 00:32:16.101
Want to tell everyone
why you have a black eye?

667
00:32:16.185 --> 00:32:18.354
Well. my brother punched me.

668
00:32:18.437 --> 00:32:19.938
I'm sorry. your brother George

669
00:32:20.022 --> 00:32:22.024
- punched you. is that right?
- Yes. ma'am.

670
00:32:22.107 --> 00:32:23.942
- Why? Yeah.
- Why?!

671
00:32:24.026 --> 00:32:26.654
Because I was
testifying against him.

672
00:32:28.656 --> 00:32:30.824
Thank you.

673
00:32:30.908 --> 00:32:32.701
Thank you. ma'am.

674
00:32:32.785 --> 00:32:34.328
No further questions.

675
00:32:41.710 --> 00:32:44.213
We know you know
a lot about drugs. Frank.

676
00:32:44.296 --> 00:32:47.591
Is that solely from
your professional experience?

677
00:32:47.675 --> 00:32:49.593
- Objection.
- I'll rephrase.

678
00:32:49.677 --> 00:32:52.346
Are you currently
taking any drugs

679
00:32:52.429 --> 00:32:55.099
that may alter
your mental state?

680
00:32:55.182 --> 00:32:57.393
I'm taking clozapine

681
00:32:57.476 --> 00:32:59.937
and. uh. lamotrigine.

682
00:33:00.020 --> 00:33:02.731
An antipsychotic
and a mood stabilizer.

683
00:33:02.815 --> 00:33:05.651
Well. you've been
to school. haven't you?

684
00:33:05.734 --> 00:33:07.945
You take those to treat
your schizoaffective disorder.

685
00:33:08.028 --> 00:33:09.488
- right?
- [Patty] Objection!

686
00:33:09.571 --> 00:33:11.591
No. this goes beyond the scope
of relevance. Your Honor.

687
00:33:11.615 --> 00:33:13.200
- Your Honor?
- Both of you. up here.

688
00:33:14.827 --> 00:33:16.471
- [Patty clears throat]
- [Griffin mutters]

689
00:33:16.495 --> 00:33:19.164
This questioning goes
straight to his credibility.

690
00:33:19.248 --> 00:33:20.708
Mental illness does not mean

691
00:33:20.791 --> 00:33:22.334
that his credibility is
impaired.

692
00:33:22.418 --> 00:33:24.002
That's for the court to decide.

693
00:33:24.086 --> 00:33:26.004
No. he is bullying
a vulnerable person.

694
00:33:26.088 --> 00:33:28.048
Your Honor. and he is
stigmatizing mental illness.

695
00:33:28.090 --> 00:33:29.967
and that is not fair.

696
00:33:30.050 --> 00:33:32.261
This witness's credibility is
the heart of this case.

697
00:33:32.344 --> 00:33:34.513
Your Honor. and I'm asking
for some leeway.

698
00:33:34.596 --> 00:33:37.307
You're playing a very
dangerous game. Mr. Petock.

699
00:33:37.391 --> 00:33:40.060
I don't see that I have
any other choice here.

700
00:33:40.144 --> 00:33:42.396
It's not my fault
the plaintiffs didn't address

701
00:33:42.479 --> 00:33:44.314
their witness's issues.

702
00:33:44.398 --> 00:33:46.483
Hmm. Objection overruled.

703
00:33:46.567 --> 00:33:48.861
You may continue. with caution.

704
00:33:48.944 --> 00:33:51.280
- Yes. Your Honor.
- [Patty sighs]

705
00:33:52.281 --> 00:33:54.742
- [Griffin] Frank?
- Yeah?

706
00:33:54.825 --> 00:33:57.161
Are you taking
this drug regimen regularly?

707
00:33:57.244 --> 00:34:00.038
Twice a day.

708
00:34:00.122 --> 00:34:03.125
And you started taking
those meds about 25 years ago.

709
00:34:03.208 --> 00:34:06.336
around the time
you left Zax Pharma?

710
00:34:06.420 --> 00:34:07.880
Could be something
like that. yeah.

711
00:34:07.963 --> 00:34:10.007
about... quarter of a century.

712
00:34:10.090 --> 00:34:12.426
Do you have
any trouble differentiating

713
00:34:12.509 --> 00:34:14.094
between reality and delusion?

714
00:34:14.178 --> 00:34:15.345
None.

715
00:34:16.680 --> 00:34:19.767
You said your brother
pushed you out of Zax Pharma

716
00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:21.810
because you tried
to stop Trimadone.

717
00:34:21.894 --> 00:34:23.645
- correct?
- That's correct.

718
00:34:26.106 --> 00:34:28.734
And that was...

719
00:34:28.817 --> 00:34:31.361
on August 5. 1994?

720
00:34:31.445 --> 00:34:32.821
- Correct?
- [Frank sighs]

721
00:34:32.905 --> 00:34:34.448
I don't know.

722
00:34:35.532 --> 00:34:37.326
Do you happen
to remember what happened

723
00:34:37.409 --> 00:34:39.453
the week before. on July 30?

724
00:34:39.536 --> 00:34:41.622
You got me. bud.

725
00:34:45.042 --> 00:34:48.212
- Does this refresh your memory?
- Objection!

726
00:34:48.295 --> 00:34:51.256
Your Honor. we don't have
whatever that is.

727
00:34:51.340 --> 00:34:53.717
Now you do. Exhibit 233.

728
00:34:53.801 --> 00:34:57.304
Any reason that you've kept
this to yourself. Mr. Petock?

729
00:34:57.387 --> 00:34:59.473
Dr. Zax is
a surprise witness. Your Honor.

730
00:34:59.556 --> 00:35:01.850
Thrown at us at the last minute.

731
00:35:01.934 --> 00:35:03.203
We're doing our best
to cross-examine him

732
00:35:03.227 --> 00:35:04.603
given the time constraints.

733
00:35:04.686 --> 00:35:07.940
Consider yourself
on a short leash. Mr. Petock.

734
00:35:09.024 --> 00:35:10.400
Can you read that report.
please?

735
00:35:10.484 --> 00:35:12.152
Just the highlighted
parts will do.

736
00:35:12.236 --> 00:35:13.821
Objection. hearsay!

737
00:35:13.904 --> 00:35:15.322
The document's over 20 years old

738
00:35:15.405 --> 00:35:16.758
and a part
of official state records.

739
00:35:16.782 --> 00:35:19.785
Overruled.
Dr. Zax. you may read.

740
00:35:19.868 --> 00:35:22.037
[Griffin] Can you please
read the report?

741
00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:24.331
I wear glasses
and they're at my house.

742
00:35:27.042 --> 00:35:29.294
Oh. of course!

743
00:35:29.378 --> 00:35:32.422
Georgie comes in!

744
00:35:32.506 --> 00:35:34.925
Happens to have
a pair of my glasses

745
00:35:35.008 --> 00:35:36.718
in his pocket

746
00:35:36.802 --> 00:35:39.137
at his trial.

747
00:35:40.597 --> 00:35:43.559
- Where do I read?
- [Griffin] Just the highlighted parts will do.

748
00:35:43.642 --> 00:35:47.271
[Frank] "Officers reporting
to the 200 block of Turk Street

749
00:35:47.354 --> 00:35:51.358
found Arthur Francis Zax.

750
00:35:51.441 --> 00:35:54.444
age 51. walking down

751
00:35:54.528 --> 00:35:57.364
the middle of the road...

752
00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:01.577
...naked
and in a state of irritability

753
00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:03.370
and confusion."

754
00:36:05.622 --> 00:36:07.541
[Frank sighs]

755
00:36:07.624 --> 00:36:10.294
"He was taken into custody

756
00:36:10.377 --> 00:36:12.880
for evaluation."

757
00:36:17.009 --> 00:36:19.595
You were suffering
through a lot of delusions

758
00:36:19.678 --> 00:36:21.263
during this period.
weren't you?

759
00:36:21.346 --> 00:36:23.056
[Frank] I don't remember.

760
00:36:23.140 --> 00:36:25.225
I know I was under

761
00:36:25.309 --> 00:36:27.060
a lot of stress.

762
00:36:27.144 --> 00:36:29.897
But. sir. this was the incident
that caused your brother

763
00:36:29.980 --> 00:36:32.357
to get you long-term.
professional care.

764
00:36:32.441 --> 00:36:34.776
- Was it not?
- He locked me up. for Christ's sake!

765
00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:36.778
You call that care?

766
00:36:36.862 --> 00:36:39.406
And you weren't removed
from Zax Pharma

767
00:36:39.489 --> 00:36:41.909
until you were declared
incompetent.

768
00:36:41.992 --> 00:36:45.621
- right?
- The man used that as an excuse

769
00:36:45.704 --> 00:36:47.414
so I couldn't stop him

770
00:36:47.497 --> 00:36:49.625
from bringing out Trimadone.

771
00:36:49.708 --> 00:36:53.462
That man took me
away from my wife...

772
00:36:54.755 --> 00:36:56.882
...and my daughter.

773
00:36:56.965 --> 00:36:59.092
[Griffin] You were married
at this time?

774
00:36:59.176 --> 00:37:00.719
Yes.

775
00:37:00.802 --> 00:37:03.347
- Where was she during this time?
- [Patty] Objection!

776
00:37:03.430 --> 00:37:05.670
What-what does this have
to do with anything. Your Honor?

777
00:37:05.724 --> 00:37:08.477
Everything. I'll be there
in three questions.

778
00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.104
You may continue.
but I am counting.

779
00:37:13.357 --> 00:37:14.816
Where was your wife. Frank?

780
00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:16.193
[Frank] I don't know.

781
00:37:16.276 --> 00:37:18.153
I was locked up.

782
00:37:18.236 --> 00:37:19.780
You told your brother

783
